      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That argument is a common one, but the evidence suggests it is more about the *design* of benefits than the existence of the safety net itself. If benefits are structured to be means-tested and phase out gradually, they can actually encourage work by preventing the \"poverty trap\" where earning more means losing all support. Policy makers are indeed debating these nuances, but the consensus is that a well-designed net supports long-term growth by preventing deep poverty and allowing workers to take risks without catastrophic consequences.",
      "source": "target",
